would report differences between `~1`, `~B`, `~A+B`, and `~A+B+A:B`. In the first case the sum of squares for `A` is comparing `~1` and `~A`, in the second case it is comparing `~B` and `~B+A`. In a non-orthogonal design (i.e., most #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:10122021220006]
two models can be compared with `anova(model1, model2)`, and `drop1(model1)` will show the sums of squares resulting from dropping single terms. #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:10122021220006]
